  "texts": [
    "The process as a whole, that is, should be hourglass-shaped.",
    "A sufficiently educated public is an obvious prerequisite for meaningful upstream public participation.",
    "While this precondition is often left unstated, it is crucial to highlight in the context of Constitutional AI, as the public currently lacks the requisite knowledge to effectively engage in these complex technical and legal matters.",
    "See Justin Blount, Zachary Elkins & Tom Ginsburg, Does the Process of Constitution-Making Matter?, in COMPARATIVE CONSTITUTIONAL DESIGN 31, 58 (Tom Ginsburg ed., 2012) (\"Secrecy, in [Jon Elster's] view, is amenable to hard bargaining, whereas publicity facilitates arguing.",
    "As a solution to this tension between transparency and secrecy, Elster employs an hourglass metaphor to describe the optimal role of the public in the process with participation via public hearings at the upstream stage and some form of ratification possible at the downstream stage."
